This paper deals with game theory and reinforcement learning, which are both subfields of computer science. The paper specifically focuses on the distribution of strategies in a game, which falls under the category of game theory (cs.GT). The use of reinforcement learning to select Nash equilibria suggests that the paper could also fall under the categories of machine learning (cs.LG) and artificial intelligence (cs.AI). Additionally, the paper involves multi-agent simulations, which could fall under the category of social and information networks (cs.SI) or multi-agent systems (cs.MA).
